        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2872582102" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15975853536500174014">For some reason every time I read a Banana Yoshimoto novel (this is my second) I expect something sinister to happen. Someone to die, a cheating spouse, some disturbing plot twist or extreme moment of violence (and I think this speaks more about me and my expectations than the author&apos;s writing). But I never get it. Instead I get the slow contemplation of someone&apos;s deep inner life. The affects on us as adults of trauma from our young lives and how it shapes us, especially the relationships we hav</span>
  <span id="freeText15975853536500174014" style="display:none">For some reason every time I read a Banana Yoshimoto novel (this is my second) I expect something sinister to happen. Someone to die, a cheating spouse, some disturbing plot twist or extreme moment of violence (and I think this speaks more about me and my expectations than the author's writing). But I never get it. Instead I get the slow contemplation of someone's deep inner life. The affects on us as adults of trauma from our young lives and how it shapes us, especially the relationships we have with others. In this case romantic relationships. <br />I found these explorations to be thoughtful as the characters navigated complex emotional relationships while trying to examine where their thinking had stalled. There was a self awareness as these characters were able to critically look at who they were and grow. But again some of these stories had such deep violent experiences that I was shocked their actions as adults weren't similar. But I suppose that ends up working out in the end. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15975853536500174014" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


