  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1331478091" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1331478091" />
    <a title="Vonia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5204784-vonia"><img alt="Vonia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610826126p2/5204784.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1331478091?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vonia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vonia" href="/user/show/5204784-vonia">Vonia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=sexuality">sexuality</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=prostitution">prostitution</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=psychology">psychology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=death-grieving">death-grieving</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=japanese">japanese</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=ghosts-spiritual">ghosts-spiritual</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=picturesque-prose">picturesque-prose</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5204784-vonia?shelf=coming-of-age">coming-of-age</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1331478091" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16857140644767869189">Banana Yoshimoto has a way with words that is unique, even from her Japanese colleagues. All her novels, short stories, and other writings have an extremely dreamlike quality, transporting, suspending the reader in whatever other world she has created with her characters. Magical realism plays an integral role, but she is always able to maintain the integrity of a moving story. Reading anything by her, however short, is an experience, and a full sensual experience at that. She ingenuously gives </span>
  <span id="freeText16857140644767869189" style="display:none">Banana Yoshimoto has a way with words that is unique, even from her Japanese colleagues. All her novels, short stories, and other writings have an extremely dreamlike quality, transporting, suspending the reader in whatever other world she has created with her characters. Magical realism plays an integral role, but she is always able to maintain the integrity of a moving story. Reading anything by her, however short, is an experience, and a full sensual experience at that. She ingenuously gives her readers to power to see, feel, hear, touch, and taste her stories - and it appears to come so easily. Her stories inescapably include some aspect of pain, whether emotional, physical, psychological, spiritual. Ghosts and the spiritual world are often an important feature. And more often than not, there is a mood of something sinister; an ominous, foreboding that enraptures the reader. This tone does not necessarily foreshadow anything negative, but is there nevertheless. Then, in my opinion the best feature of all her books, is that psychological insight; her ability to somehow lyrically, lucidly express emotions and situations, poetically describe that feeling we have all experienced but never knew how to translate into words. The things Yoshimoto does with and/or in her writing are something one needs to experience for themselves, for words will not suffice. Her writings? Absolutely, undeniably affecting. This collection of short stories, my fourth Banana Yoshimoto experience, was no exception. <br /><br />Aside from Yoshimoto's lyrical words with the magical effect her readers have learned to expect, the stories in the collection share themes of change, time/timing, fate, healing, discovering ones identity, rediscovering paths in life, &amp; perseverance. <br /><br />In "Newlywed", a young man whom is having early doubts regarding his marriage meets a spiritual guide (Angel?) on his train home, after he unexpectedly decides to remain seated at his stop. After his encounter, in which he is able to re - experience some of his better times with his wife and gain another perspective on his current situation, he decides to return home.<br /><br />In "Lizard", a man with a tragic, pained past (His mother committed suicide after being raped by her brother-in-law), is drawn to a young woman with an equally sad childhood (her mother was assaulted in front of her; it would have been mortal, but the young girl learned that night that she had the power to heal others). The two lovers visit a shrine in Narita, where they share their secrets and revel in the beauty of miracles and life, changes and new beginnings.<br /><br />"Helix" revolves around the proposition that an individual can choose to have their memory erased of everything but that which is necessary. The female protagonist is the one in favor of this, attending a seminar next week. The male protagonist, her boyfriend, has his doubts. What is "necessary" defined as in this context? According to whom? What if one wishes to retain those memories that are, maybe, unnecessary, but sentimental and warming nonetheless? What if it will only be "necessary" alongside a memory yet to be created? These are the risks the girl would be taking.<br /><br />"Dreaming of Kimchee" tells the story of "The Other Woman" - but "The Other Woman" that wins the husband eventually. She struggles with guilt and then paranoia ("Once a cheater, always a cheater"), but finally finds solace.<br /><br />The penultimate story in the collection, "Blood + Water", is the most straightforward coming-of-age story in the collection, highlighting the importance in identity. The young female narrator has escaped to Tokyo to pave her own way, leaving everything she loves and knows in a Buddhist sect, cult-like religious village, though her parents, the other villagers she was raised with have treated her with nothing but compassion. She feels the temptation to return after a year, but meets someone whom changes this. He is the introspective artist type; the sculptures he creates have the ability to heal their recipients. They learn from each other, lean on each other, furthering the potential in their young love.<br /><br />The protagonist in "A Tale From Down By The River" also has a less than ideal history. Her mother had a psychological failure shortly after giving birth to her, her husband unable to stay faithful. She throws her infant into the rushing river, and is unable to coherently communicate for several months afterwards. Fortunately, both she and her daughter are rescued by the husband. They both recover in time physically, but the emotional effects last longer; most notably in the daughter, the now adult protagonist. For many years, she was in the depths of sex addiction, ending it only when she discovered a medical condition. She has now found a kindred soul in her fiance. Their residence is a beautiful loft overlooking a river. The close proximity of the river, her parents visiting her, the change in values, and her decisions to alter her ways of life result in her parents finally revealing the circumstances of her birth to her, providing the opportunity to finally discover who she wants to be. When her fiance is anonymously sent evidence of her past in sexual promiscuity, yet is determined to stay loyal to their love, she is able to understand, for the first time, what it feels like to be understood, to belong to someone and somewhere; she finally experiences unadorned love.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16857140644767869189" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1331478091">
