<div id="review_1569944667" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1569944667" />
    <a title="Hez" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25260119-hez"><img alt="Hez" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623323630p2/25260119.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1569944667?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hez" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hez" href="/user/show/25260119-hez">Hez</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1569944667" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9502853870262109056">Almost tasteless combination of trash-mag cover stories (&quot;I lost my voice when Mum was stabbed my a home invader! &quot;, &quot;I used to be a sex addict and now I&apos;m married to the heir of a company fortune! &quot;), with &quot;the feelings of disorientation, apprehension and uncertainly that accompany most attempts at sorting out one&apos;s own emotional baggage, as well as the feelings of liberation that some people have at crucial times in their lives&quot; (author).<br/>This is uncommonly pragmatic. There is grief but the cha</span>
  <span id="freeText9502853870262109056" style="display:none">Almost tasteless combination of trash-mag cover stories ("I lost my voice when Mum was stabbed my a home invader! ", "I used to be a sex addict and now I'm married to the heir of a company fortune! "), with "the feelings of disorientation, apprehension and uncertainly that accompany most attempts at sorting out one's own emotional baggage, as well as the feelings of liberation that some people have at crucial times in their lives" (author).<br />This is uncommonly pragmatic. There is grief but the characters still dig their lives. There is no escape into cathartic despair or even black humor. (and it's not a fake Kerouacian fun-time on an alcohol drip (author's possible alcohol-use notwithstanding). <br />It's almost steely-eyed. All the time I read Yoshimoto I'm cringing at every "gorgeous" (just swimming out of my demographic? are they just paint on top of some emotionless ness?) but then the one in the last paragraph of this book made sense.<br />We need more modern myths like this to help us through the tough times. Not on the road but at home. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9502853870262109056" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


