<div id="review_2636228747" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2636228747" />
    <a title="Claire" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/71846415-claire"><img alt="Claire" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2636228747?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Claire" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Claire" href="/user/show/71846415-claire">Claire</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571212156" href="/book/show/50148.Lizard">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2636228747" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6584944858305003002">Banana Yoshimoto&apos;s Lizard is a collection of short stories, each focused on how we create hope and purpose in our lives,and find the path we want to walk as individuals in a busy, modern world. Newlywed tells the story of a young man, who encounters something phenomenal while fighting the urge to escape the responsibility a newly wedded life, Lizard the story of a couple reconciling with troubling pasts. Helix also discusses commitment from the perspective of a young writer, Dreaming of Kimchee </span>
  <span id="freeText6584944858305003002" style="display:none">Banana Yoshimoto's Lizard is a collection of short stories, each focused on how we create hope and purpose in our lives,and find the path we want to walk as individuals in a busy, modern world. Newlywed tells the story of a young man, who encounters something phenomenal while fighting the urge to escape the responsibility a newly wedded life, Lizard the story of a couple reconciling with troubling pasts. Helix also discusses commitment from the perspective of a young writer, Dreaming of Kimchee about trust and the paranoia accompanying a history of infidelity, Blood and Water about a cynical woman accepting her roots in a Buddhist sect, and lastly A Strange Tale from Down by the River about a woman leaving behind an unusual and adventurous past in pursuit of happiness and health. Each story tackles the theme of marriage and the end of youth gracefully, following a winding path that's never quite as simple as one might think. <br /><br /> Lizard is more than a collection of short stories. It is a collection of so many of the qualities that have brought Yoshimoto such a broad, devoted audience. Each story encapsulates one of many outlooks on life, and follows the journey we as humans follow to understand and accept the truth of our lives and circumstances, expanding the day-to-day and transforming it into the extraordinary. Though Helix was not as interesting as the other short stories, richer stories like the titular Lizard make up the difference. The simple language makes the book accessible enough, and by no means a challenging read. <br /><br />I would recommend this book to young adults unsure of their place in life, or to older teenagers anticipating such things. Though it is directed mainly at women, I think that being a woman is not necessary to enjoy the book- books for young women and teenagers are often dismissed as not being real literature, but Yoshimoto's stories have a universal appeal. Though it takes place in Japan, a large background of knowledge in Japanese culture is not needed to understand the text, as it is contemporary and focuses on relationships as opposed to setting. <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6584944858305003002" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


